In competitive frisbee events, the most well-known sport is Ultimate Frisbee, now simply known as "Ultimate." It is a non-contact, self-refereed team sport played with a flying disc or Frisbee. The objective of the game is to score points by passing the Frisbee to a teammate who catches it in the opposing team's end zone. Each team typically consists of seven players, although variations of the game with different team sizes exist.

Some common rules for the sport of Ultimate include:

1. Players may not run while holding the disc (i.e., the person holding the disc must maintain a pivot foot and cannot move beyond that foot);
2. A player has ten seconds to throw the disc. If they don't throw within that time, the opposing team takes possession;
3. Players can advance the disc only by passing it to their teammates. Passes can be made in any direction;
4. When the disc is caught in the opponent's end zone, a point is scored;
5. If a pass is incomplete (e.g., dropped, intercepted, thrown out of bounds), the opposing team gains possession of the disc where the incompletion occurred;
6. There is no physical contact allowed between players. Contact results in a foul, and the player who committed the foul gives possession to the other team;
7. Spirit of the Game is a crucial aspect of Ultimate Frisbee. Players are expected to exhibit sportsmanship, fair play, and respect for their opponents and teammates.

Ultimate is played in various settings and levels, from casual pick-up games to high-level club teams and professional leagues. There are other competitive frisbee sports as well, such as disc golf and freestyle, which have their own unique objectives, rules, and gameplay styles. However, Ultimate remains the most popular and internationally recognized competitive frisbee sport.

